> A peek into later chapters: ==Any signal can be written as a sum of sinusoids==

### Representing frequency
$$x(t)=\cos(2\pi f_0t)$$
- $x(0)=1$
- $x(2\pi)=1$
- Note the sinusoid is periodic. After a fundamental period $T_0$, its values repeat

![period.png|300](data:image/png;base64,)

**Units of frequency**
- $T_0$ = period [s, s/cycle]
- $f_0$ = frequency (hertzian) [Hz, s^-1, cycle/s]
- $\omega_0$ = frequency (radian) [rad/s]
	- $\omega_0=2\pi f_0= \frac{2\pi}{T_0}$

### Defining a sinusoid
**Most general form of a sinusoid**
$$x(t)=A\cos(2\pi f_0 t+\phi)$$

==Three parameters== that define a sinusoid
- amplitude
- frequency
- phase (can be derived from time delay -- see [[02 georgia-tech/sum22/ECE2026/05.18 Lecture - ECE2026#Converting Equivalences|05.18 Lecture - ECE2026#Converting Equivalences]])


## Standard Form

![Pasted image 20220518154413.png](data:image/png;base64,)

“Standard form” constraints make parameters in a sinusoid *unique*
- $f_0\geq 0$
- $A \geq 0$
- $-\pi < \phi \leq \pi$

## Converting Equivalences

**Two skills**
1. From formula to plot
2. From plot to formula

Both based on **equivalence of delay and phase shift**:
$$A\cos(\omega(t-t_0))=A\cos(\omega t+\phi)$$
- Therefore, $\phi=-\omega t_0$ ⭐⭐⭐
- $t_0$ is also written as t_p (time of peak) and t_p (time delay)

### Skill 1: Given formula/equation, draw plot

$$x(t)=5cos(0.2\pi t-0.4\pi)$$

**Solution**
![Pasted image 20220518162231.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)

**Steps**
- Locate the first peak, which can be found by setting cos() arguments to 0
- Locate another peak by setting cos() arguments to $2\pi$
- Location of peak at t=10s
	- $0.2\pi t=2\pi$
- Determine the phase
	- $0.2\pi t - 0.4\pi = 0.2\pi(t-t_d)$
	- $t_d=2$

> Note: You can arrive at the next peak by incrementing/decrementing by T_0=1/f_0. Additionally, when using the formula, the time for any peak can be chosen. The simplest choice would be the closest peak $t_p=-0.2$ in this example

### Skill 2: Given plot, write formula

![Pasted image 20220518162242.png](data:image/png;base64,)

**Solution**
1. Measure time between peaks $T_0$
2. Measure time delay $t_d$. In this case, you can use $t_a$ (wait i have some words here)
3. Measure amplitude $A$

Last step: Multiply everything out

$$x(t)=12\cos(1.25\pi t+0.25\pi)$$

## Representing Sinusoids via Complex Exponentials

**Euler**
$$e^{j\theta}=\cos\theta+j\sin\theta$$

**Graphically, plotted on the unit circle**
- Fixed value of theta
- Results in an triangle with length values able to be determined using trig functions

## Complex Amplitude

To get a *general sinusoid*, change from a set magnitude of 1 to a general <u>complex amplitude</u> (which represents the starting point in a rotating phasor)
$$X=Ae^{j\phi}$$
- Circle radius A
- Starting angle phi
- Introduces phase and amplitude to our “pure sinusoid”


**Going back to Euler’s**
$$z=re^{j\theta}=A\cos\theta+jA\sin\theta$$
Theta is a function of time
$$\theta(t)=\omega t+\phi$$
Therefore…
$$z(t)=Ae^{j(\omega t+\phi)}=A\cos(\omega t + \phi)+jA\sin(\omega t+\phi)$$

*Note real component of z(t) looks familiar!*
![Pasted image 20220526114703.png](data:image/png;base64,)

> **Important to note**
> - Starting vector * frequency of rotation
> - $z(t)=Ae^{j\phi}e^{j\omega t}$ 

### Complex Amplitude Represents
![Pasted image 20220526114810.png](data:image/png;base64,)

> Note how more compact it is to represent sinusoids in polar form and complex amplitudes, as we know the frequency.

## Sum of Sinusoids

**Motivating question**: What is the result of the following expression?
$$1.1\cos(70\pi t+0.1\pi)+0.8\cos(70\pi t - 0.6\pi)$$

While not as obvious, the sum is also a sinusoid, of the same frequency!

### Key Result
![Pasted image 20220526115221.png](data:image/png;base64,)

The sum of 2 sinusoids having the same frequency is a *single* sinusoid of that frequency, regardless of amplitudes and phases!

### Why? Phasors Make it Clear
![Pasted image 20220526115344.png](data:image/png;base64,)
- Essentially, thinking geometrically again, we are adding the starting position of the two sinusoids, which are represented in the complex amplitude
- Essentially performing vector addition


## Phasor addition rule
Here it is, restated once more
$$\sum\limits_iA_i\cos(\omega t+\phi_i)=\sum\limits\Re\{z_i(t)\}$$
$$z_i=A_ie^{j\phi_i}e^{j\omega t}$$
$$\Re\set{\sum\limits_iz_i}\qquad\rightarrow\qquad\sum\limits_iz_i=(\sum\limits_iA_ie^{j\phi_i})e^{j\omega t}$$
We know: $\Re\set{z_1+z_2}=\Re\set{z_1}+\Re\set{z_2}$
- Vector addition

Any number of sinusoids can be added this way
- Important condition: All sinusoids must have the same frequency


**Exercise**
$1.1e^{j0.1\pi}+0.8e^{-j0.6\pi}=Ae^{j\phi}$
- Would be solved using a calculator
- A represents the combined magnitude
- phi represents the combined phase
